%N A393404 Sum of the smallest parts in the partitions of n into 3 parts whose largest part is even.
%H A393404 <a href="/index/Par#part">Index entries for sequences related to partitions</a>
%H A393404 <a href="/index/Rec#order_17">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (1,0,0,1,-1,2,-2,0,0,-2,2,-1,1,0,0,1,-1).
%F A393404 a(n) = Sum_{j=1..floor(n/3)} Sum_{k=j..floor((n-j)/2)} j * ((n-j-k+1) mod 2).
%F A393404 a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-4) - a(n-5) + 2*a(n-6) - 2*a(n-7) - 2*a(n-10) + 2*a(n-11) - a(n-12) + a(n-13) + a(n-16) - a(n-17).
%F A393404 a(n) + A393409(n) + A309694(n) = n*A026927(n). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Feb 17 2026
%e A393404 a(10) = 9; There are 5 partitions of 10 into 3 parts whose largest part is even: (8,1,1), (6,3,1), (6,2,2), (4,4,2) and (4,3,3). The sum of the smallest parts of these partitions is 1+1+2+2+3 = 9.
%t A393404 Table[Sum[Sum[j*Mod[n - j - k + 1, 2], {k, j, Floor[(n - j)/2]}], {j, Floor[n/3]}], {n, 0, 100}]
